{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"nl -ba task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md | sed -n '52,92p'\nnl -ba .claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md | sed -n '15,32p'\nnl -ba .claude/plans/loloop/evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-action-model-schema.md | sed -n '1,80p'\"","aggregated_output":"    52\t- `events/events.jsonl`: append-only event stream. Each line is one JSON object with `event_id`, `type`, `timestamp`, and event-specific fields such as `task_id`, `agent_id`, `workspace`, or `payload`.\n    53\t- `inbox/<agent_id>.jsonl`: append-only per-agent messages. Each line is one JSON object with `message_id`, `target_agent_id`, `created_at`, `type`, and message-specific fields such as `task_id`, `agent_id`, or `payload`.\n    54\t- `agents/<agent_id>.json`: latest known agent state with `agent_id`, `state`, `current_task_id`, `heartbeat_at`, `last_error`, and `updated_at`.\n    55\t- `views/`: reserved for generated read models. It must not become the source of truth for task, event, inbox, or agent state.\n    56\t\n    57\tIDs should remain filename-safe. Structured writes should prefer `tasks/`, `events/`, `inbox/`, and `agents/` over parsing free text from `team.md`.\n    58\t\n    59\t## Task 3 — Supervisor and Worker Flow\n    60\t\n    61\t- [ ] keep supervisor actions explicit: initialize, assign, inspect, recover, and handoff\n    62\t- [ ] support worker actions as mailbox events only: claim, heartbeat, blocked, complete\n    63\t- [x] attach a result envelope shape to completion events so future automation can inspect outcomes\n    64\t- [ ] define stale-lease recovery behavior before adding background reclamation automation\n    65\t\n    66\t## Supervisor and Worker Action Model\n    67\t\n    68\tCurrent mailbox action boundaries:\n    69\t\n    70\t- Supervisor actions are explicit host/dashboard actions: initialize team space, assign a task to a live thread, inspect mailbox-derived team state, recover by re-reading mailbox files on refresh, and receive handoffs through events plus supervisor inbox messages.\n    71\t- Worker actions are represented as mailbox state transitions plus append-only events: claim, heartbeat/progress, blocked, and complete.\n    72\t- Worker blocked and complete actions also notify the supervisor through `inbox/supervisor.jsonl`.\n    73\t- This model does not route work through board tabs and does not replace legacy thread lifecycle state.\n    74\t\n    75\t## Completion Result Envelope\n    76\t\n    77\tCompletion events use the same result envelope stored on the task record and sent as the `payload` of `task.completed` events:\n    78\t\n    79\t- `summary`: non-empty human-readable completion summary.\n    80\t- `outputs`: array of produced artifact references or paths.\n    81\t- `checks_run`: array of validation commands or checks performed.\n    82\t- `open_risks`: array of known residual risks, blockers, or caveats.\n    83\t- `next_request`: optional follow-up request for the supervisor.\n    84\t\n    85\t## Task 4 — Non-Destructive Dashboard Surface\n    86\t\n    87\t- [x] surface mailbox summary in overview without reshaping existing overview cards\n    88\t- [x] expose thread-level team controls only inside bounded surfaces such as the drawer\n    89\t- [x] avoid overloading current board tab semantics with team routing semantics\n    90\t- [x] make the team surface clearly secondary when mailbox mode is not initialized\n    91\t\n    92\t## Task 5 — Loop Automation Defaults\n    15\t- `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n    16\t\n    17\t## Current Slice\n    18\t\n    19\t- [ ] Analysis slice — audit the Task 3 supervisor/worker action-model note against current runtime behavior.\n    20\t\n    21\t## Next Handoff\n    22\t\n    23\t- Loop type just completed: execution; the Task 3 supervisor/worker action-model note was added without runtime changes.\n    24\t- Keep the mailbox cadence at 1